WEBVTT

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:01.770
Yina Arenas:
Hello.

00:00:01.770 --> 00:00:04.211
Welcome to Building Smart AI

00:00:04.223 --> 00:00:07.290
Systems in Foundry,
as everything

00:00:07.290 --> 00:00:10.260
in the world evolves around us.

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:12.780
I'm Yina. I lead Product
for Microsoft Foundry.

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:16.110
And I'm joined today with
Naomi, who does all the work

00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:19.920
for shipping all of the
models in Microsoft Foundry.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.830
And in the next 45 minutes,
we're going to talk

00:00:22.830 --> 00:00:26.910
about something that every
team building with AI faces.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:30.840
You build the systems,
and the landscape

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:32.280
around you keeps evolving.

00:00:32.280 --> 00:00:37.230
The models, the tools, the set
of capabilities around them,

00:00:37.230 --> 00:00:40.190
it's all shifting around you.

00:00:40.190 --> 00:00:42.380
And let's be honest, a year ago,

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:44.930
building an AI app felt
a lot more simple.

00:00:44.930 --> 00:00:47.930
You pick the model, you wire
it up, and you ship it.

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:50.880
But now you're no longer
building just chat apps.

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:55.170
You're full-on building agentic
systems, long-running systems

00:00:55.170 --> 00:00:58.290
that have to
continuously improve.

00:00:58.290 --> 00:01:01.890
And that is a little
bit more challenging.

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:06.210
And here's what I see every
single developer face, run into.

00:01:06.210 --> 00:01:09.690
They have a hard time picking
the right model for the task.

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:11.490
There's a lot of
models in the market.

00:01:11.490 --> 00:01:13.590
More keep coming
every single day.

00:01:13.590 --> 00:01:16.170
The benchmarks look great on
paper, but they don't tell you

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:19.020
if their model is good
for your scenario.

00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:21.680
And then the costs are really,
really hard to predict.

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:25.160
And then you can
do some analysis

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:27.500
when you're building it, but
when you put it into production

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:29.510
and see the bill, it's painful.

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:34.490
Right? So, the moment
that you have something

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:37.200
that is fully built
and out there,

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:39.330
then the next model is
in, the next tool is out,

00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:41.340
and all of these different
things need to keep changing.

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:44.550
And you have to continuously
be building this system,

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:48.060
and the landscape keeps
moving around you.

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:52.560
Now, what you want is a system
that is simpler, that is better,

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:55.950
that is more cost-effective, and
that is scalable as you bring it

00:01:55.950 --> 00:01:58.350
into production, and that
gives you the best outcome

00:01:58.350 --> 00:01:59.790
for your scenario.

00:01:59.790 --> 00:02:01.860
And today we're going to show
you how you can actually get

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:06.330
there using Microsoft Foundry
as the underlying platform.

00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:07.260
What you need in order

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:10.230
to get there is not just
a better prompt system,

00:02:10.230 --> 00:02:14.970
or a newer model, or
the latest MCP tool.

00:02:14.970 --> 00:02:18.060
What you need is a system that
continuously improves over time

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:21.450
and a platform that enables
you all the way from building

00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:23.930
to governing and
managing at scale.

00:02:23.930 --> 00:02:27.650
For that, we start with building
with GitHub Copilot CLI,

00:02:27.650 --> 00:02:29.276
grounding with
all of the sets of

00:02:29.288 --> 00:02:30.830
information that you might have

00:02:30.830 --> 00:02:32.000
within your organization,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.940
whether it is your
productivity data in Work IQ,

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:40.080
your structured data in
Fabric IQ, all of the context

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:41.580
and knowledge that you
might want to bring

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:43.200
to your agents using Foundry IQ,

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:45.810
and all of the world's
knowledge using Web IQ.

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:49.560
Then running that in Foundry
using Foundry-hosted agents,

00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:52.980
governing with A365, and then
improving over time with a set

00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:55.830
of platform capabilities
that Foundry offers.

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:57.540
And that's where
Foundry comes in.

00:02:57.540 --> 00:03:02.040
It's the platform that
enables you to take models,

00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:05.370
agent service, all of the
grounding information,

00:03:05.370 --> 00:03:09.840
the tools, the post-training
capabilities, and bring that all

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:13.230
to bear for you to
leverage in your scenario.

00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:14.610
And the platform
is fully governed

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:16.500
for the entire
agentic lifecycle,

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:18.420
not just for running inferencing

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:21.570
or for building a specific
point-on solution.

00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:23.940
It's for you to be
able to build, deploy,

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:25.230
and operate at scale,

00:03:25.230 --> 00:03:29.010
and continuously improve
your entire system.

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:32.520
And this is an
important mental shift.

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:35.220
And if there's, I will say,
one thing that you take

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:38.250
out of this session
today, it's how we need

00:03:38.250 --> 00:03:43.230
to evolve how we think about
what was QA-ing our solutions.

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:45.540
So as a developer, you used
to think about I'll build it,

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:48.480
and then I'll think
about QA at the end.

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:51.480
Actually, that needs to
be entirely shifted left,

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:54.390
and now you have to think
about your success criteria

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:57.540
and evaluation first, so
that then you can think

00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:00.270
about how you're going to
continuously improve over time

00:04:00.270 --> 00:04:03.180
and build a resilient
solution that decouples

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:07.020
from the model evolving,
from tools changing,

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:09.420
and from the context
evolving itself.

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:11.880
That way, you can
actually build a solution

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:16.890
that is more ready
for the test of time.

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:20.430
And there's a set of
optimization categories,

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:21.660
I'll just go back for a second,

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:23.103
that then, once you have your

00:04:23.115 --> 00:04:24.870
evaluations
defined, are actually

00:04:24.870 --> 00:04:28.110
going to tell you, what are the
set of levers that you can pull

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:29.400
to optimize the system.

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:30.180
And this is how we're going

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:31.890
to structure the rest
