00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:19.170
Yina Arenas:
Yeah, think about it as like,

00:18:19.170 --> 00:18:20.850
when you're building an
enterprise solution,

00:18:20.850 --> 00:18:22.770
you want to think about
microservices architecture

00:18:22.770 --> 00:18:26.130
and not using a single model for
everything in your solution.

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:26.940
Break it apart.

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:28.320
What are the jobs to be done?

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:29.790
And for each of the
jobs to be done,

00:18:29.790 --> 00:18:32.310
you can optimize a specific
model that you use for that.

00:18:32.310 --> 00:18:34.440
And the smaller the model,
the faster you can do it,

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:37.260
and the more cost you can
have on optimization.

00:18:37.260 --> 00:18:40.650
Then, one of the best ways,
and the simplest ways

00:18:40.650 --> 00:18:42.930
that you can use
when you decompose

00:18:42.930 --> 00:18:45.360
into multiple models is
to use a model router.

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:47.010
The model router
takes, automatically,

00:18:47.010 --> 00:18:50.010
the prompts that you have,
and then will analyze,

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:52.080
based on the prompt,
which is the best model

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.090
to send the request to.

00:18:54.090 --> 00:18:56.340
We have in Foundry
a model router.

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:59.760
And, actually, it supports
28 different models,

00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:05.280
including GPT-5.4, GPT-5.5
family, Claude Opus models.

00:19:05.280 --> 00:19:08.070
And then it has, also, automatic
failover to improve all

00:19:08.070 --> 00:19:09.450
of the customer experience.

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:11.040
It has agentic support.

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:14.160
And also, starting today,
we're now being able

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:17.400
to govern the policies of
which models are being used

00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:21.300
by model router so that from
a governance perspective,

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:22.860
you can auto-select
just the models

00:19:22.860 --> 00:19:25.200
that you want your solution to,

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:27.990
or that you might want
your solution just to use.

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:31.020
We're also investing more on
model routers so that further

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:33.540
down the line, we're going to
open the ability to customize,

00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:35.400
to fine-tune the router itself,

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:38.850
and to bring in
fine-tuned models.

00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:41.610
The second way that you can do,
instead of using a model router,

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:43.650
is, where you build
a router yourself.

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:47.910
And you have a small model
that routes the intent.

