00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:40.970
And then, we can
still work on some

00:21:40.970 --> 00:21:43.590
of these other
areas, like latency.

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:47.070
Let's keep going.

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:49.830
So, when you think about model
selection, it's really coming

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:51.870
down to these three
different questions.

00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:54.450
So, oftentimes we think about,
whether you're choosing

00:21:54.450 --> 00:21:55.890
that model, it's
whether you think

00:21:55.890 --> 00:21:57.480
about that capability
piece of it.

00:21:57.480 --> 00:22:00.000
Can it even do the job
at all a part of this?

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.820
We also want to think about,
what's the bar for production.

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:04.620
When we're looking at
latency, when we're looking

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:06.450
at cost optimization,
can it do the job

00:22:06.450 --> 00:22:08.130
that you need inside
of production?

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:10.980
And then, of course, can you
afford to run it at that scale?

00:22:10.980 --> 00:22:13.530
This is the other piece
of when people often look

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:15.810
at these different
areas, it's like, costs

00:22:15.810 --> 00:22:18.480
and those pieces really
play a big factor

00:22:18.480 --> 00:22:20.070
into how you scale up.

00:22:20.070 --> 00:22:22.920
So benchmarks, of course,
can help you in this case.

00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:25.470
They can understand a little bit
more about where you're going.

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:27.450
But they shouldn't make
the decision for you.

00:22:27.450 --> 00:22:29.550
And it's a really important
piece of looking at this.

00:22:29.550 --> 00:22:33.330
The answer comes from your
workload, what model to use,

00:22:33.330 --> 00:22:36.240
evaluate on your workload,
not the beautiful benchmarks

00:22:36.240 --> 00:22:38.160
that are out there
as part of this.

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:41.790
So, let's go into evaluating and
understanding a little bit more.

00:22:41.790 --> 00:22:42.240
Yina Arenas:
Yeah.

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:45.090
This is a great segue, because
that's what we're saying, is,

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:47.220
benchmarks is not
necessarily what is going

00:22:47.220 --> 00:22:49.680
to lead your decision making
in selecting a model.

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:52.260
It's how do you
evaluate on your data,

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:54.840
and that should drive
your model selection.

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:59.010
As part of Foundry, we
have an extensive model

00:22:59.010 --> 00:23:00.600
and evaluation catalog.

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:04.140
But the key, again, key
point of the session,

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:05.670
start with evaluations.

00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:06.720
And in the improvement loop,

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:08.970
the evaluation becomes
your product spec.

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:12.150
And as you're hill climbing,
the evaluations become your IP.

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:15.570
This is where you're going
to have your data come in,

00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:18.210
your success criteria,
and the definition

00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:21.330
of what good looks like for you.

00:23:21.330 --> 00:23:24.090
It defines which trade-offs
are going to matter for you,

00:23:24.090 --> 00:23:26.730
and it's the measuring stick
for every single change

00:23:26.730 --> 00:23:28.500
that you're going to
make to the system,

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:32.040
whether that change is something
that you're making, or something

00:23:32.040 --> 00:23:34.680
that you have to react to, like,
for example, model lifecycle.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:36.870
The model is no longer
available in the catalog.

00:23:36.870 --> 00:23:38.130
Now what are you going to do?

00:23:38.130 --> 00:23:41.940
You have to continuously
run this set of evaluations

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:45.420
to make sure that as you bring
in a new set of components

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:47.220
to your solution,
you can continue

00:23:47.220 --> 00:23:49.740
to run as you're expecting.

00:23:49.740 --> 00:23:52.110
So, for this specific
scenario that we're using

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:54.030
on the planner trip evaluation,

00:23:54.030 --> 00:23:56.760
things like correctness,
policy compliance.

00:23:56.760 --> 00:23:58.890
And when I say "policy,"
