00:29:00.450 --> 00:29:02.310
We've gone through these
different segments.

00:29:02.310 --> 00:29:04.350
And so, we want to make
sure that cost reduction

00:29:04.350 --> 00:29:07.890
in AI rarely comes from just
choosing a cheaper model.

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:09.540
I see customers doing
this all the time.

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:11.520
I'm sure you all have
tried this as well.

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:13.320
Don't think about it as
being a cheaper model.

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:15.510
It is about the
architectural decisions

00:29:15.510 --> 00:29:18.630
that you are making inside
of your application.

00:29:18.630 --> 00:29:21.000
So, optimization is
that hill climb.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.550
You can see that we've got the
categories on the side, here,

00:29:23.550 --> 00:29:26.640
that helps us to understand
these multiple dimensions.

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:29.070
So, we're not just pushing
on cost in this case.

00:29:29.070 --> 00:29:30.570
We're actually
pushing on quality

00:29:30.570 --> 00:29:32.100
or just pushing on latency.

00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:35.100
We need to find a way to
improve the system meaningfully

00:29:35.100 --> 00:29:36.990
across all of these dimensions.

00:29:36.990 --> 00:29:39.240
And so, that's why we want
to think about optimization

00:29:39.240 --> 00:29:41.610
as a really iterative
process through this.

00:29:41.610 --> 00:29:43.890
You start off with things
like prompt improvements.

00:29:43.890 --> 00:29:46.380
You're going to carry on with
better context, and then,

00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:49.680
essentially, have decomposition
routing as we showed and then,

00:29:49.680 --> 00:29:53.280
of course, deeper architectural
latency here, levers here.

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:55.770
So, you want to think about
maybe the goal is not having a

00:29:55.770 --> 00:29:57.210
perfect endpoint.

00:29:57.210 --> 00:30:00.090
It's really about how do we
make that system really operate

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:04.500
and measurable faster and better
with every single choice.

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:07.470
So, when teams talk about AI
cost, and I'm sure you all think

00:30:07.470 --> 00:30:10.200
about cost, can I show of
hands folks who are thinking

00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:11.430
about costs in
their applications?

00:30:11.430 --> 00:30:14.010
Almost, I would say, at least
three-quarters of the room.

00:30:14.010 --> 00:30:15.450
The rest of you are
obviously ballers

00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:17.070
for all of your AI token use.

00:30:17.070 --> 00:30:18.330
So, it's all good.

00:30:18.330 --> 00:30:21.900
So, when teams talk about
this AI cost piece of this,

00:30:21.900 --> 00:30:24.330
the instinct is to ask
for that cheaper model.

00:30:24.330 --> 00:30:26.970
But in practice, it's actually
the biggest wins are coming

00:30:26.970 --> 00:30:28.470
from those system designs.

00:30:28.470 --> 00:30:31.680
We have a full stack of
levers inside of Foundry.

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:33.690
And so, I often think
about, here, hey,

00:30:33.690 --> 00:30:35.430
can I do routing by workload?

00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:37.410
Can I make sure I'm
using batch inference?

00:30:37.410 --> 00:30:38.820
Right? That can save
you lots of money

00:30:38.820 --> 00:30:40.020
as part of what we're doing.

00:30:40.020 --> 00:30:41.460
You can think about
that async jobs.

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:44.160
We've got structured outputs
here for wasted tokens,

00:30:44.160 --> 00:30:46.860
caching here to help you
avoid those repeated work,

00:30:46.860 --> 00:30:49.980
and distillation that brings
down some of the cost as well.

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:52.290
The important point is,
for every single one

00:30:52.290 --> 00:30:54.870
of these levers,
those gains compound.

00:30:54.870 --> 00:30:56.730
So, think about it
across that spectrum.

00:30:56.730 --> 00:30:59.280
You're basically not just
doing one magical fix,

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:01.080
as much as we would all
love that to happen.

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:03.330
You basically need an
architecture that helps you

00:31:03.330 --> 00:31:05.850
to take advantage of that
and lets you stack all

00:31:05.850 --> 00:31:08.310
of those optimizations together.

00:31:08.310 --> 00:31:10.110
So, that brings me into caching.

00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:12.030
Caching is a big
area for all of us.

00:31:12.030 --> 00:31:14.520
We've been on this journey
for implicit caching.

00:31:14.520 --> 00:31:16.890
We've been into this
expanding out, as we think

00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:18.510
about different areas of caching

00:31:18.510 --> 00:31:20.520
and how they've been
improved over time.

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:22.290
And so today, we're
really excited

00:31:22.290 --> 00:31:24.030
to have an optimization
that's coming

00:31:24.030 --> 00:31:26.130
to caching that's
new and different.

00:31:26.130 --> 00:31:27.510
So, caching has really evolved

00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:29.310
from that low-level
optimization.

00:31:29.310 --> 00:31:30.900
And we want to make
sure as part of this,

00:31:30.900 --> 00:31:33.180
we have explicit prompt caching.

00:31:33.180 --> 00:31:35.340
Explicit prompt caching
